Title : List of Call the Midwife episodes
Text : {{featured list}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}
{{Use British English|date=October 2016}}
[[File:Call the midwife box set series 1-4.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The cover of the DVD box set comprising the first four series and three Christmas specials|alt=Four nurses on the top half of the cover; nuns on the bottom half]]
''[[Call the Midwife]]'' is a British [[period drama]] television series based on the best-selling memoirs of former nurse [[Jennifer Worth]], who died shortly before the first episode was broadcast.<ref name="gru" /> It is set in the late 1950s and early 1960s and for the first three series centred primarily on Jenny Lee ([[Jessica Raine]]), who, in the first episode, begins a new job as a midwife at a nursing convent in the deprived [[Poplar, London|Poplar]] district of London. The programme's [[ensemble cast]] has also included [[Jenny Agutter]], [[Pam Ferris]], [[Judy Parfitt]] and [[Laura Main]] as nuns living at the convent, and [[Miranda Hart]], [[Helen George]], [[Bryony Hannah]], [[Charlotte Ritchie]] and [[Emerald Fennell]] as other midwives. [[Vanessa Redgrave]] delivers framing voiceovers in the role of "mature Jenny",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2012/030112midwife.html|title=Call the Midwife|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=12 March 2013}}</ref> and continues to do so even after the younger version of the character was written out of the series.

The idea of adapting Worth's books for television was initially dismissed by the [[BBC]],<ref name="gru" /> but revived after [[Danny Cohen (television executive)|Danny Cohen]] took over the post of [[BBC One#Controllers of BBC One|Controller]] of [[BBC One]]. A full series was commissioned in 2011<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2011/06_june/17/midwife.shtml|title=Call The Midwife, new drama series for BBC One starring Jenny Agutter, Pam Ferris and Miranda Hart|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=17 June 2011|accessdate=12 March 2013}}</ref> and writer [[Heidi Thomas]] adapted Worth's books for the screen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2013-02-12/call-the-midwife-creator-heidi-thomas-tv-series-wont-suffer-when-source-material-runs-out|title=Call the Midwife creator Heidi Thomas: TV series won't suffer when source material runs out|first=Jack|last=Seale|work=[[Radio Times]]|date=12 February 2013|accessdate=12 March 2013}}</ref> The first episode was broadcast on 15 January 2012 and the initial series of six episodes drew positive reviews and large viewing figures, said by the BBC to be the highest audiences achieved by a new drama series on BBC One since the corporation's current method of measuring audiences began in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/9093475/Call-the-Midwife-is-the-most-watched-BBC-One-drama-in-10-years.html|title=Call the Midwife is the most-watched BBC One drama in 10 years|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|first=Andrew|last=Marszal|date=20 February 2012|accessdate=12 March 2013}}</ref> Following the second episode, the BBC announced that a second series, expanded from six to eight episodes, had been commissioned.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/jan/23/bbc-call-the-midwife|title=BBC Calls the Midwife for a second series|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=23 January 2012|accessdate=12 March 2013|first=Mark|last=Sweney}}</ref> In September 2012 the programme won the Best New Drama award and Hart was named Best Actress at the ''[[TV Choice]]'' Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a405010/tvchoice-awards-2012-the-winners-in-full.html|title=TVChoice Awards 2012: The winners &ndash; In full|first=Colin|last=Daniels|publisher=[[Digital Spy]]|date=10 September 2012|accessdate=12 March 2013}}</ref>

The second series began on 20 January 2013, and during the run BBC Controller for Drama Ben Stephenson announced that he had commissioned a third series to be broadcast in 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2013/ben-stephenson-bbcdrama.html|title=BBC Controller of Drama, Ben Stephenson, sets out his vision for drama on the BBC and announces new commissions|date=11 February 2013|accessdate=24 February 2013|publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref> despite the fact that all the original source material had been exhausted by the end of the second series.<ref name="gru">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2013/feb/12/bbc-call-midwife-commissioned-third-series|title=Call the Midwife commissioned for third series and Christmas special|work=[[The Guardian]]|first=John|last=Plunkett|date=12 February 2013|accessdate=12 March 2013}}</ref> The series has also achieved success outside the UK. In the United States, the first series' transmission on [[PBS]] in the autumn of 2012 drew an average audience of three&nbsp;million viewers. This figure was 50% higher than the network's overall primetime average audience for the 2011&ndash;12 television season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/about/news/archive/2012/call-the-midwife-2/|title=BBC and PBS to bring second season of critically acclaimed drama "Call the Midwife" to the U.S.|accessdate=12 March 2013|publisher=[[PBS]]}}</ref>

{{Aired episodes|2019|3|3|uk=y|title=Call the Midwife|finished=8}} In March 2019, the BBC announced it had commissioned two further series and Christmas specials, through to an eleventh series in 2022, moving the plot into the late 1960s.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-47441282 |title=Call the Midwife gets two more series |publisher=BBC |date=4 March 2019 |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/bbc-itv-renew-call-the-midwife-endeavor-vera-1203154143/ |title=British Dramas ‘Call the Midwife, ‘Endeavour,’ ‘Vera’ Get New Seasons |work=Variety |first=Stewart |last=Clarke |date=4 March 2019 |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref>

